{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658930"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:58:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:58:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20838"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20838"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13713"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97047"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13713"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20838"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79663"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11597"},{"type":"tags","id":"12329"},{"type":"tags","id":"12352"},{"type":"tags","id":"12662"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33018"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33019"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97047"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECancer development is influenced by multiple risk factors, including lifestyle choices, environmental exposures, and infectious agents. Understanding these risk factors is essential for developing effective prevention strategies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most significant environmental risk factor contributing to premature death from cancer in developed countries?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alcohol consumption","Infectious agents","Cigarette smoking","Ultraviolet radiation","Obesity"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECigarette smoking\u003C/strong\u003E is the single most important environmental factor contributing to premature death in developed countries. It is implicated in about 90% of lung cancers and also increases risk for cancers of the mouth, pharynx, larynx, oesophagus, pancreas, and bladder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfectious agents\u003C/strong\u003E cause approximately 15% of all cancers worldwide, but the burden is roughly three times higher in developing countries than in developed countries. Examples include human papillomavirus (HPV) which causes cervical cancer and some head and neck cancers.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol consumption\u003C/strong\u003E increases the risk of cancers of the oropharynx, larynx, and oesophagus. It also contributes to hepatocellular carcinoma through alcoholic cirrhosis. While significant, its impact is not as widespread as cigarette smoking.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObesity\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with increased cancer risk, with the most overweight individuals having 52% (men) to 62% (women) higher death rates from cancer. Approximately 14% of cancer deaths in men and 20% in women are associated with obesity. However, this is still less than the impact of smoking.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltraviolet radiation\u003C/strong\u003E is an environmental carcinogen that primarily increases risk for skin cancers. While significant, its overall contribution to cancer mortality is less than that of cigarette smoking.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these risk factors is crucial for developing effective cancer prevention strategies, with smoking cessation representing one of the most impactful interventions for reducing cancer mortality.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Approximately 15% of all cancers worldwide are caused by infectious agents, with a higher burden in developing countries.","Cigarette smoking is implicated in about 90% of lung cancers and increases risk for cancers of the mouth, pharynx, larynx, oesophagus, pancreas, and bladder.","Obesity is associated with increased cancer mortality, contributing to approximately 14% of cancer deaths in men and 20% in women.","Environmental carcinogens include ultraviolet radiation, asbestos, arsenic, and various workplace exposures."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 7; page 278."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79663"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20838"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79663"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-04T06:53:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-04T06:54:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13713"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97047"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11597"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Neoplasia","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":6,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount